# .trivyignore — Trivy vulnerability suppression list
#
# Format: one CVE ID per line, with a comment explaining the accepted risk.
# Docs: https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/#trivyignore
#
# Before adding a CVE here, verify ALL of the following:
#   1. The vulnerability has been assessed and is not exploitable in our context, OR
#   2. No upstream fix is available and mitigating controls are in place, OR
#   3. It is a confirmed false positive for our use case.
#
# Each suppression MUST include:
#   - The CVE ID
#   - A comment with: reason, date assessed, ticket/owner
#
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Example entries (remove and replace with real suppressions as needed):
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# CVE-YYYY-XXXXX
# Reason: <why this is accepted or not applicable>
# Assessed: YYYY-MM-DD | Ticket: UNC-XXX | Owner: <team>

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# node:20-alpine base image — known low-impact musl libc findings
# These are flagged by Trivy but do not affect our runtime attack surface
# because they require local access (no remote exploitation vector).
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# CVE-2023-4039
# Reason: GCC stack protection false positive on alpine; no executable stack
# in our Node.js services. Assessed: 2026-03-17 | Owner: platform-security
# CVE-2023-4039
